                         Content: v.--> <inline font-size="9pt" font-style="italic"> [Note: <inline font-style="italic" font-weight="normal"><inline font-style="italic">V.c.</inline>4.<inline font-style="italic">n.</inline>30.</inline>] </inline> that are shut up in the cells, not medling with an of their own Sex.</block><block line-height="1" text-indent="1em" space-before.optimum="0pt" space-before.maximum="12pt"><inline font-size="9pt" font-style="italic"> [Note: 45. <inline font-style="italic">Hearing and feeling.</inline>] </inline> Their hearing and feeling are verie quicke. If you touch their Hive but lightly, or the stoole, or the ground neere it; they presentlie perceiving it, make a generall noise: <inline font-size="9pt" font-style="italic"> [Note: <inline font-style="italic" font-weight="normal">Hist.an.l.9.cap.40.</inline>] </inline> although <inline font-style="normal" font-weight="normal">Aristotle</inline> doubt whether they heare, or not. ‘<inline font-style="italic" font-weight="normal">Quanquam incertum est an audiant.</inline>’ But if they did not heare, to what purpose is that musicke made in the Hives, before the swarming? <inline font-style="italic" font-weight="normal"><inline font-style="italic">v.c.</inline>5.<inline font-style="italic">n</inline>28</inline>. and in the battaile, <inline font-style="italic" font-weight="normal">vid.c.</inline>7.<inline font-style="italic">n.</inline>34. or his tinging of swarmes to make them come downe, <!--An internal link should have been created here,
